# Principles	for	effective	visualizations


---

## Principles	for	effective	visualizations

- Order matters
- Put long categories on the y-axis
- Keep	scales consistent
- Select meaningful colors
- Use meaningful and nonredundant labels

---


## Data

In September 2019, YouGov survey asked 1,639 GB adults the following question:

.pull-left[
> In hindsight, do you think Britain was right/wrong to vote to leave EU?
>
>- Right to leave  
>- Wrong to leave  
>- Don't know

]
.pull-right[

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

:::

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](u2-d14-effective-dataviz_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-6-1.png){fig-align='center' width=100%}
:::
:::

]

.footnote[ 
Source: [YouGov Survey Results](https://d25d2506sfb94s.cloudfront.net/cumulus_uploads/document/x0msmggx08/YouGov%20-%20Brexit%20and%202019%20election.pdf), retrieved Oct 7, 2019
]


---

class: middle

# Order matters

---


## Alphabetical order is rarely ideal

.panelset[

.panel[.panel-name[Plot]

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](u2-d14-effective-dataviz_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-7-1.png){fig-align='center' width=60%}
:::
:::

]

.panel[.panel-name[Code]

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(brexit, aes(x = opinion)) +
  geom_bar()
```
:::

]

]


---

## Order by frequency

.panelset[

.panel[.panel-name[Plot]
::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](u2-d14-effective-dataviz_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-8-1.png){fig-align='center' width=60%}
:::
:::
]

.panel[.panel-name[Code]

`fct_infreq`: Reorder factors' levels by frequency

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(brexit, aes(x = fct_infreq(opinion))) + #<<
  geom_bar()
```
:::
]

]

---


## Clean up labels

.panelset[

.panel[.panel-name[Plot]

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](u2-d14-effective-dataviz_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-9-1.png){fig-align='center' width=60%}
:::
:::

]

.panel[.panel-name[Code]


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(brexit, aes(x = opinion)) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs( #<<
    x = "Opinion", #<<
    y = "Count" #<<
  ) #<<
```
:::

]

]


---

## Alphabetical order is rarely ideal

.panelset[

.panel[.panel-name[Plot]
::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](u2-d14-effective-dataviz_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-10-1.png){fig-align='center' width=60%}
:::
:::
]

.panel[.panel-name[Code]

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(brexit, aes(x = region)) +
  geom_bar()
```
:::
]

]

---


## Use inherent level order

.panelset[

.panel[.panel-name[Relevel]

`fct_relevel`: Reorder factor levels using a custom order


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
brexit <- brexit %>%
  mutate(
    region = fct_relevel( #<<
      region,
      "london", "rest_of_south", "midlands_wales", "north", "scot"
    )
  )
```
:::

]

.panel[.panel-name[Plot]

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](u2-d14-effective-dataviz_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-11-1.png){fig-align='center' width=60%}
:::
:::

]

]


---

## Clean up labels

.panelset[

.panel[.panel-name[Recode]

`fct_recode`: Change factor levels by hand

::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
brexit <- brexit %>%
  mutate(
    region = fct_recode( #<<
      region,
      London = "london",
      `Rest of South` = "rest_of_south",
      `Midlands / Wales` = "midlands_wales",
      North = "north",
      Scotland = "scot"
    )
  )
```
:::
]

.panel[.panel-name[Plot]
::: {.cell layout-align="center"}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](u2-d14-effective-dataviz_files/figure-html/recode-plot-1.png){fig-align='center' width=60%}
:::
:::
]

]

